        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 4. <placeName type="townland"
                    >Kilmannin</placeName></name>, Co. 
                <placeName type="county">Mayo</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=MA093-045003-"
                >MA093-045003-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Ecclesiastical</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Possible early ecclesiastical site (<hi rend="italic">Cill Mhainín</hi>) with a tradition of a Killeen.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>Re-used in the construction of a church. <rs type="material">'Stratified
                            sandstone'</rs>,
                        <rs type="dimensions"> <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height"
                                >1.22</measure>m x <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width"
                                >0.51</measure>m x <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth"
                                >0.3</measure>m <lb/> (converted from <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >6</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</rs>
                    </p>
                    </div>

                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>The stone is inscribed on all four angles with what appears to be two inscriptions (one surrounding each face, up-top-down), the second of which is unintelligible. 
                        In the latter, three letters from the end, <q>S2 and S3 are seen to form a character resembling a 6, broken at the bottom</q>, which <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >7</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> suggests looks like the U-<hi rend="italic">forfid</hi>, but it could be just damage to the stone.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>
                    <persName><w lemma="LUGADDON">
                        LUGADDON
                    </w></persName>
                    <w lemma="MAQI" type="formula">MA<unclear reason="worn">Q</unclear>/I</w>
                    <persName><w lemma="LUGUDECAS">LUGU/DEC</w></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/> DDISI/ MO<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/><unclear reason="damage">C</unclear>QU<unclear reason="unusual">S</unclear>/EL</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p><lb n="1"/><q>of <persName>Lugáed</persName> son of
                    <persName>Luguid</persName></q></p>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-images">
                    <head>3D Images</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                    <lb/>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url="Kilmannin 4(1).JPG"/>
                    </figure>
                    <lb/>
                    <list type="bulleted">
                        <item n="1"><ref
                                target="http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/html/004x001l.htm"
                                >http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/html/004x001l.htm</ref></item>
                        <item n="2"><ref
                                target="http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/html/004x003l.htm"
                                >http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/html/004x003l.htm</ref></item>
                    </list>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                    <lb/>
                    <p><name type="author">Macalister</name><ptr type="bibiog" target="#MAC1945"
                            />:<ref
                            target="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/archaeology/cisp/database/picpage/kilma_1_1.html"
                            >http://www.ucl.ac.uk/archaeology/cisp/database/picpage/kilma_1_1.html</ref></p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>Compound of two personal names (<persName><hi rend="italic">Lug</hi></persName>, divine
                        name and <persName><hi rend="italic">Aidonas</hi></persName>),
                        <foreign>*<hi rend="italic">lugu-aidonas</hi></foreign>, with compositional vowel <hi rend="italic">u</hi> before
                        vowel giving /<hi rend="italic">w</hi>/ in 1. <placeName type="findspot">Inchagoill
                                Island</placeName>, <placeName type="county">Galway</placeName>
                        (Latin inscription – <persName xml:lang="la">LUGUAEDON</persName>) but <hi rend="italic">u</hi> 
                        lost/dropped in <foreign>LUGADDON</foreign> <ref
                            target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">117</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. However, this may <q>reflect 
                                    the reduction of the diphthong in unstressed position to /ə/</q> <ref
                                        target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                            >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">121</biblScope></bibl></ref>; <ref
                                target="#UHL1989"><bibl><author>Uhlich</author> <date>1989</date>,
                                    <biblScope type="pp">131 n9</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p><persName><hi rend="italic">Lug</hi></persName> and <persName><hi rend="italic">Decas</hi></persName> 
                        (<foreign>*<hi rend="italic">dek</hi></foreign>- <gloss>'to show respect'</gloss>) <ref
                            target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">103, 178 n.17</biblScope></bibl></ref>), cp.
                                <name type="stone">263. <placeName type="findspot"
                                    >Ardmore</placeName>, <placeName type="county"
                                    >Waterford</placeName></name> (<foreign>LUGUDECAS</foreign>);
                                <name type="stone">286. <placeName type="findspot"
                                    >Kilgrovan</placeName>, <placeName type="county"
                                    >Waterford</placeName></name> (<foreign>LUGUDECA</foreign>);
                                <name type="name">108. <placeName type="findspot">Kilcullen
                                    South</placeName>, <placeName type="county"
                                >Cork</placeName></name> (<foreign>LUGUDUC</foreign> for
                                -<foreign>DEC</foreign>?). </p></item>
                    <item n="3"><p><ref
                                target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1991"
                                    >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">113</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> notes
                            this inscription as an example of the repetition of an element of the
                            father's name in the son's. </p></item>
                     <item n="4"><p>This inscription may be approximately dated to the 
                        <origDate notBefore="0540" notAfter="0600">middle or second half of the sixth century</origDate> 
                        owing to the absence of endings in the names (-DON, earlier -DONAS; 
                        -DEC, earlier -DECAS) while the ending -I is retained in the formula word MAQI <ref
                            target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">95, 97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">'built into the wall of an old church' <ref
                            type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author> <date
                                when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp">6</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> 
                        at <placeName type="townland">Kilmannin</placeName>, barony of <placeName
                            type="barony">Costello</placeName>. The original location of this stone
                        may be accessed via the <ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=MA093-045003-"
                            >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                            www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                        <geo>-8.765218,53.773045</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="location">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs></p>
                </div>
